stories: My concern is the imbalance between remote townships and central municipalities when it comes to County resources. Please, readers of the countryside, don't get defensive just yet. The way it stands now, most businesses, not individuals, contribute to the County's income. It struck me that rural areas are deprived of essential services, like decent libraries, healthcare clinics, or reliable public transport. I've noticed County-funded projects in major cities, such as stadium renovations, expensive office builds, and a vast personnel network, leaving townships vulnerable. A broadcast I watched highlighted the efforts of volunteers revitalizing aging town squares – it got me wondering, why not allocate some of those resources to urban rejuvenation instead? Yes, I pay county taxes too. But I'm convinced once townships shoulder the entirety of the burden, we'll adopt a more frugal approach, considering each and every expense. In my previous profession, as a small business owner, I'd ask my team, "what unnecessary expenditures could we eliminate?"
